            .</p>
               <p>SUSANNAH COLLINS. I live at No. 1, Sharp's-alley, and am a <rs id="t18310217-221-viclabel1294" type="occupation">widow</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-221-victim2076 t18310217-221-viclabel1294"></join>. I have a shed near <placeName id="t18310217-221-crimeloc1295">Grey Eagle-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-221-crimeloc1295" type="placeName" value="Grey Eagle-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-221-crimeloc1295" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-221-off1292 t18310217-221-crimeloc1295"></join>, which was secured by an iron padlock - I went there about eight o'clock in the morning, on the 15th of January, found it had been broken open, and missed about twelve sacks of soot; I found a handkerchief, which I gave to the officer- I had seen my shed safe on the night before; the soot I missed was worth 30s., it is 2s. 6d. a sack - I traced some sooty foot-marks, from Grey Eagle-street to the top of Pearl-street, opposite Fleur-de-lis-court; it was a damp morning, and that was the reason I suppose.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-221-person2077">
                  SAMUEL 
                  ONION
               <interp inst="t18310217-221-person2077" type="surname" value="ONION"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-221-person2077" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-221-person2077" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an apprentice to Mr. Peter Savage, Moore's-alley, Norton-falgate - he is a chimney-sweep. I have known the prisoner these five years; he was in the habit of bringing soot to my master, about six months before he was taken - when he was engaged in shooting the soot, I used to hold his cap, and I used to see a handkerchief in it; I observed it particularly - I noticed a tear in the corner, and three letters on it; I have had it twenty times in my hand - there was a cook-shop at the corner of Moore's-alley, which he used to frequent, and I have seen him use the handkerchief there; I remember on one occasion, we were standing at the corner of Cock-alley, and he had it in his hand - we used to call him by the nickname of Buss, and I said, "Buss, let me look at your handkerchief;" I looked at it, and said, "It is torn at the corner;" he said, "I know it is;" there were three letters on it in a straight line - this is the handkerchief, here is the tear; here are three letters in a straight line, and one below; I had not noticed the one below at that time.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. When did I show you the handkerchief? A. I cannot rightly tell; it was about three days before this happened.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183102170127"></xptr>JURY. Q. How long before he was apprehended had you seen him shoot any soot? A. About six months - he was not in my master's employ, but he used to buy soot of the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-221-person2078">
                  JOHN 
                  BURNESS
               <interp inst="t18310217-221-person2078" type="surname" value="BURNESS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-221-person2078" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-221-person2078" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a private watchman. I was at the corner of Fleur-de-lis-court, on the morning of the 15th of January, and saw two sweeps - one had a sack of soot on his back, and the other was following him; they came as if from Grey Eagle-street, which is about one hundred yards from there - I saw them return twice with empty sacks; I saw them afterwards in Blossom-street - Barnard was following them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-221-person2079">
                  BENJAMIN 
                  BARNARD
               <interp inst="t18310217-221-person2079" type="surname" value="BARNARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-221-person2079" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-221-person2079" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw two men carrying soot - I believe the prisoner was one, but cannot swear it.</p>
